 bacteria. He takes readers from Rome's pinnacle in the second century, when the empire seemed an invincible superpower, to its unraveling by the seventh century, when Rome was politically fragmented and materially depleted. Harper describes how the Romans were resilient in the face of enormous environmental stress, until the besieged empire could no longer withstand the combined challenges of a "little ice age" and recurrent outbreaks of bubonic plague.A poignant reflection on humanity's intimate relationship with the environment, The Fate of Rome provides a sweeping account of how one of history's greatest civilizations encountered and endured, yet ultimately succumbed to the cumulative burden of nature's violence. The example of Rome is a timely reminder that climate change and germ evolution have shaped the world we inhabit-in ways that are surprising and profound.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aClimate and civilizationzRome. 0aClimatic changes. 0aEpidemicszRome. 0aHuman beingsxEffect of climate on. 0aRegression (Civilization). 0aRomexCivilization. 0aRomexHistoryxEmpire, 30 B.c.-476 A.d. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh  aCOVID-19.  aWuhan.  acoronavirus deaths in us.  acoronavirus deaths.  acoronavirus map.  acoronavirus usa cases.  acoronavirus.  anovel coronavirus.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054332240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400888917zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400888917423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400888917.jpg  a978-3-11-054332-2  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Hu